<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-405-650  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 405 650.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  July 3 1989 n424 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Industry lobby group goes public: systems vendors' organizationadds Apple, Cray and NCR as members. (The Computer Systems PolicyProject)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Computer Systems Policy Project, a new lobbying group composedof U.S.andP;  computer vendors, hopes to influence public policyaffecting their international competitiveness.andP;  Specifically, thegroup is concerned with trade, dumping laws, scientific educationand long-term industry vision.andP;  Members include Apple ComputerInc, Cray Research Inc, NCR Corp, Compaq Computer Corp, HP, IBM,Sun Microsystems Inc, Tandem Computers, and Unisys Corp. ATandamp;T,Control Data Corp, DEC, Prime Computer Inc and Tektronix Inc areinvited to join.andP;  The 1986 U.S.-Japan Semiconductor TradeArrangement is expected to be one of the first issues of focus.andO;Heads of member firms are to compose the group's board.andP;  Memberfirms' government relations representatives will compose asecond-level board responsible for developing lobbying strategies.andO;The group's first meeting is set for early fall 1989 butactivities are expected to begin informally before then.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer Systems Policy ProjectLobbyingTrade and Professional AssociationsMembership ListGoals and ObjectivesInternational TradeEducationFuture of Computing.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   The Computer Systems Policy Project's top priorities. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>